  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.1419" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <opener>My dear Sir,</opener>
        <p>Your kind favor of Nov. 15<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> is just received. Please accept my best thanks for the same.</p>
        <p>I hope, without doubt, to have the pleasure &amp; great honor of meeting you next summer. I assure you that a personal acquaintance on my part would be most highly esteemed.</p>
        <p>Your “<hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">über Schurri murri n. s. w. </hi>[sic]“<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Gemeint ist der folgende Artikel: <bibl>
              <ref
                  target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.658">
Schuchardt, Hugo. 1884. 'Zu meiner Schrift 'Slawo-deutsches' und 'Slawo-italienisches''. In <hi
                  rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Zeitschrift für die österreichischen Gymnasien</hi> 35: 900-901.</ref>
            </bibl> [Archiv-/Breviernummer: 161].</note> never reached me. I should be delighted to have it, if you still have extra copies. Such writing as yours is what we need extremely in America &amp; I assure you that you are doing a fine missionary labor, not only for Europe but America.</p>
        <p>I am looking forward with great pleasure to your “<note n="2" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Der Titel des Schuchardt-werkes wurde nicht eingefügt.</note> which I shall gladly notice. <pb
            facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/> We are now at work on the first number of <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">“Modern Language Notes”</hi>,<note n="3" place="foot"
              type="editorial">Die Zeitschrift <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.3343">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Modern Language Notes</hi>
            </ref> wurde 1886 gegrundet und wird bis heute von der <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5346">
Johns Hopkins University</ref> veröffentlicht. </note> a monthly publication in which we shall be able to make all such matters as these known extensively among our colleagues in the United States.</p>
        <p>I am now at work on my second article on the Canadian Language,<note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>

Elliott, Aaron Marshall. 1886. ‘Speech-Mixture in French Canada. External Influence.‘ In <hi
                rend="unknown" rendition="#none">American Journal of Philology</hi> VII, 2:141:160.
</bibl>
          </note> where I treat the strong external influences (social, religious + civil) that had a tendency to produce a homogenous speech in that country.</p>

        <p>I regret, my dear Sir, to hear that you are not very well. I have also been a great sufferer from neurasthenia, but fortunately now am much better from the liberal use of cold baths, the only thing that <pb
            facs="#IMG.3" n="3"/> has ever helped me much.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours very sincerely,</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1447">A. M. Elliott</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
        <postscript>
          <p>Prof. H. Schuchardt – </p>
          <p>Graz.</p>
        </postscript>
      </div>
